    difficultyRating: 4,
    weatherImpact:
      "Qatar's desert climate delivers warm to hot conditions even in November and October. Unlike Bahrain, where the desert is relatively still, Qatar can experience dust-laden winds that blow onto the circuit from the surrounding desert, compromising track grip and visibility. The night race format means air temperatures are somewhat manageable, but the tarmac retains heat from the afternoon sun and track temperatures are very high at the start of the race. Dust and sand on the track surface — particularly off the racing line — create significant grip differentials that affect tyre behaviour and car balance. The high-speed nature of the corners means any loss of aerodynamic stability due to gusty conditions is amplified.",
