  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // AUTODROMO JOSE CARLOS PACE (INTERLAGOS) — Brazilian Grand Prix
  // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  interlagos: {
    summary:
      "The Autodromo José Carlos Pace, universally known as Interlagos, is a compact, anti-clockwise circuit in São Paulo, Brazil, that has produced more dramatic and emotional moments than perhaps any other circuit in Formula 1. Situated in a natural bowl, the circuit's layout creates a natural amphitheatre where the predominantly passionate Brazilian crowd can see most of the track simultaneously. The unusual combination of a tight, technical infield with a long, sweeping main straight creates a uniquely varied challenge, and the unpredictable São Paulo weather — famous for sudden, heavy tropical downpours — means almost every Brazilian Grand Prix has at least one extraordinary moment.",
    location: "São Paulo, Brazil",
    country: "Brazil",
    trackType: "Permanent road circuit",
    length: "4.309 km (2.677 miles)",
    raceDistance: "305.879 km (190.064 miles)",
    laps: 71,
    turns: 15,
    drsZones: 2,
    firstGrandPrix: "1973",
    lapRecord: "1:10.540",
    lapRecordHolder: "Valtteri Bottas",
    lapRecordYear: "2018",
    difficulty: "Hard",
    difficultyRating: 4,
    weatherImpact:
      "São Paulo in November sits at the beginning of the tropical wet season, and the Brazilian Grand Prix is one of the most weather-affected races on the calendar. Sudden, heavy afternoon thunderstorms are almost a tradition — the circuit's position in a valley means storm systems can appear very quickly and with great intensity. The 2008 Brazilian Grand Prix, one of the most dramatic races in the sport's history, began in dry conditions and then saw a rain shower in the dying laps completely transform the championship picture. When rain falls at Interlagos, the bumpy, ageing asphalt creates aquaplaning risks, and the spray in the tight infield sections drastically reduces visibility. Wet conditions here are chaotic and exciting in equal measure.",
    overtakingDifficulty: "Moderate — the main straight and Senna S provide overtaking chances, while the anti-clockwise layout and tyre degradation differences create strategic variability",
    famousFor:
      "Interlagos is most famous as the scene of some of the most emotionally charged moments in Formula 1 history. The 2008 Brazilian Grand Prix is legendary — Lewis Hamilton went into the final race of the season needing to finish fifth or higher to win his first championship; on the final lap, in the rain, he dropped to sixth and the championship appeared lost before Timo Glock, struggling on slick tyres in the wet, was passed by Hamilton on the final corner of the final lap, giving Hamilton the championship by one point in the most dramatic sporting finish imaginable. It is also the home of the Senna family — Ayrton Senna is the most revered person in Brazilian history, and racing in his memory at his home circuit carries extraordinary emotional weight.",
    history:
      "Interlagos first hosted a Formula 1 Grand Prix in 1973 and is one of the oldest circuits still on the calendar in its basic configuration. The original circuit was much longer — 7.873 km — but was shortened to its current configuration in 1990 after a major refurbishment. The circuit sits on the southern outskirts of São Paulo in the Interlagos neighbourhood, literally meaning 'between the lakes' in Portuguese, a reference to two artificial lakes that surround the venue. Ayrton Senna won his home Grand Prix three times here, and his funeral in 1994 following his death at Imola drew three million people to the streets of São Paulo in the largest public gathering in Brazilian history. Interlagos's future on the calendar has occasionally been questioned due to the poor state of São Paulo's infrastructure, but the race's emotional significance has always ensured its survival.",
    keyCorners: [
      "Senna S (Turns 1–2) — The first two corners of the lap; a fast, sweeping left-right 'S-bend' named after Ayrton Senna; the circuit drops downhill through here and cars carry significant speed on entry",
      "Descida do Lago — A fast, downhill sequence of corners following the Senna S; the road drops dramatically into the infield, creating unique loading on the car",
      "Ferradura (Horseshoe) — A slow, tight hairpin at the lowest point of the circuit; the primary overtaking opportunity from the back straight",
      "Mergulho — An extremely fast, blind downhill left-hander; taken near flat-out, it is one of the most commitment-demanding corners on the calendar",
      "Bico de Pato — A slow hairpin at the end of the back straight; the second DRS zone ends here, making it the secondary overtaking opportunity",
      "Junção — A fast, sweeping right-hander leading onto the main straight; maximising speed through here is critical for the approach to Senna S"
    ],
    funFacts: [
      "The 2008 Brazilian Grand Prix is universally regarded as the most dramatic championship finale in Formula 1 history — Lewis Hamilton secured his first world title by passing Timo Glock in the final corner of the final lap, moving from 6th to 5th position and winning the championship by a single point.",
      "Interlagos means 'between the lakes' in Portuguese — the circuit sits between two artificial reservoirs, the Guarapiranga and Billings reservoirs, that provide much of São Paulo's drinking water.",
      "Ayrton Senna's 1991 home victory is one of the most emotional in the sport's history — he crossed the line in tears, unable to change gear in the final laps due to a broken gearbox, steering with one hand and shifting manually with the other.",
      "The circuit runs anti-clockwise, which is unusual — drivers turn right more than left, placing unusual loads on the right-hand tyres and requiring reverse engineering of conventional setup logic.",
      "São Paulo is one of the most crime-affected cities in the world, and the Formula 1 paddock has experienced security incidents including helicopter approaches by local criminals over the years; the paddock perimeter security is among the most extensive of any circuit.",
      "Nigel Mansell clinched his 1992 World Championship with victory at Interlagos — technically not at this circuit but it was the closest race geographically; the actual 1992 Brazilian GP was held at Interlagos where Nigel Mansell won on his way to the title."
    ],
    image: "/circuits/interlagos/hero.jpg",
    mapImage: "/circuits/interlagos/map.png"
  },

